    <p> Today I would like to tell how I came to diving and what huge fun it can. </p>
    <p> To get briefly. I was already diving in my life in front of this diving course and thought it was great. I was diving for the first time when I was 13 in the Warnem&uuml;nder swimming pool. There was a huge children's day party with trial diving. We friends Carola, Peer and I thought the idea was great to try it all out. The second way to dive gave me Qype a few years ago. In the deepest winter we went to a outdoor pool with about 20 people. It was cold. Asskin! But it was great anyway. </p>
    <p> When it was clear to me that I would go to Australia it was immediately clear that I would like to go diving at the Great Barrier Reef and, if possible, not just once. After some surfing on the Internet, I even found that you can visit the reef there even without an official diving certificate with diving instructors. The prices for this are really a hearty. Often the two to triple the price, as for divers with a diving license. </p>
    <p> Two weeks ago I sat at my desk again and smelled of great deals at Groupon and stumbled across a diving course for just $ 199 at Prodive. I almost couldn't believe that and made myself smart about the diving school. Some colleagues already knew the branch in the Coogee district and were able to assure me that he was not bad at all. Now I took a closer look at the offer and it turned out where to save here. You have to do the theoretical part alone via an online platform before the practical part can start. Well, I should get that. The practical part is then done for 3 days. 1 day in the pool and 2 days in the open water. </p>
  </div>
