  <div class="col-md-7">
    <p> As we all know, I am not the fittest and not the slimest. Therefore, I am recommended to go to the diving doctor in the offer to have me checked through. In Sydney's city center, diving doctors are a lot more expensive for this but they also speak German. The test was a matter of about an hour and showed me that I am actually relatively fit, apart from my overweight. Can even hear better than I would have expected. So nothing stood in the way of the diving license. </p>
    <p> After a short consultation with my boss because of the practice days, I now booked the offer. When booking, I still had the choice between two different certifications. SSI and Padi. </p>
    <p> Since Padi was supposed to cost around $ 150 and a short research on the net showed me that both certificates are almost equally recognized, I decided on the cheaper Varainte SSI. The online training of SSI is even completely free of charge and can be completed without booking the practical part. </p>
    <p> Now that I had the voucher to have a practical date (April 8th, 2013 - April 10th, 2013) and had booked and booked the theory. As so often, the theory was a bit dry. It cost a few afternoons and promised to box through the reading and to answer the questionnaires that appear again and again. </p>
  </div>
