  <div class="col-md-7">
    <p> After the online theory was through, the practical days now started. First of all, we had to watch 3 videos about diving security and take a check -up test to prove that we also read and understood the theoretical part. Next we searched for the equipment and drove to the outdoor pool in Victoria Park. </p>
    <p> Once there, I jumped into my wetsuit and first had to swim a few lanes and then step for 10 minutes without holding on to somewhere. This was not that easy if you should do it with many others in a small area. Then we were divided into two groups and we were explained again in practice how the equipment is built up and tested. Then it went back into the water. There we then did the compulsory exercises such as pulling and taking off the diving equipment in and under water or the ventilation of the diving goggles under water. </p>
    <p> It also turned out that I had a fairly high air consumption under water. Since we stayed in the pool for a few hours, I also needed a new tank in between. At the very end we all had to get out of the water and then bounce into the back on the back. I immediately found that the last task and I will not be friends. I find the feeling stupid to bounce into the water with so much extra weight. </p>
  </div>
