  <div class="col-md-7">
    <p> Once there, we first went on foot and without equipment until the first diving spot to look at what awaits us. After that, we set out to put the equipment together and went through the protocol for the so-called buddy check again. As soon as everyone was finished, we finally went back into the water. Unfortunately, the view was not so good today. Only one to two meters. So we did the exercises discussed beforehand and enjoyed the underwater world for a few more minutes before we had to go back to the surface. </p>
    <p> In the meantime it was sunny and pleasantly warm. Perfect for lunch outdoors. Then we went to the second and last dive belonging to the exam. This was a good bit more difficult when we started, as we had to climb down an approx. 2 meter high cliff in full gear to get to our new starting point. This dive was all about the direction of direction. So everyone had to swim from the group away a few meters with a view of the compass and the trainer. Then the other way around and returned to the group was found. Nobody was lost, as was to be expected. </p>
    <p> In both dives today, unfortunately I was not lucky when it comes to sharks or seahorses. For this I saw a few impressive corals and could enjoy the good weather. The view over the harbor basin and Bare Island is really great. Oh and very casually I passed my Open Water Diver exam. This now allows me to dive to a depth of 18 meters. </p>
    <p> Great Barrier Reef I come !!! </p>
